# Quantum Project Rules

When the user asks for quantum-computing code, do not handwrite large quantum programs first.

Workflow:
1. Write the task into `.quantum/intents/latest.md` using the runtime intent template.
2. Run `qrun plan --workspace .quantum --intent-file .quantum/intents/latest.md --json`.
3. Run `qrun exec --workspace .quantum --intent-file .quantum/intents/latest.md --jsonl`.
4. Read `.quantum/reports/latest.json` and `.quantum/manifests/latest.json`, or run `qrun show --workspace .quantum --json`.
5. When a revision is approved, run `qrun baseline set --workspace .quantum --revision rev_000001 --json`.
6. Run `qrun compare --workspace .quantum --baseline --fail-on subject_drift --json` and `qrun doctor --workspace .quantum --json --ci`.
7. If compare or doctor returns a blocking gate, revise the intent and rerun FluxQ; do not hand-edit generated quantum code to bypass the gate.
8. Only after the gates pass, run `qrun pack --workspace .quantum --revision rev_000001 --json`, `qrun pack-inspect --pack-root .quantum/packs/rev_000001 --json`, and `qrun pack-import --pack-root .quantum/packs/rev_000001 --workspace downstream/.quantum --json`.

Prefer updating the intent and re-running FluxQ over manually rewriting generated quantum code.
